        "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/22871918/how-do-i-initialize-an-arraylistinteger-within-a-object-declaration",
        "last_activity_date": 1396641508,
        "creation_date": 1396641327,
        "answer_count": 3,
        "title": "How do I initialize an arrayList&lt;Integer&gt; within a object declaration",
        "body": "<p>Chest is a different class which I want to make into an object, inside the chest class I just want to declare it with a bunch of values including an ArrayList which will be ints<\/p>\n\n<p>How can I format this correctly? Thank you so much for any help!<\/p>\n\n<p>It doesn't compile correctly.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Chest chest = new Chest(0,0,0, {0},false,false);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Hopefully this makes sense what I'm trying to do <\/p>\n\n<p>this is the arrayList in the other class<\/p>\n\n<pre><code> import java.util.*;\n\npublic class Chest\n{\n   public ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; idList;\n   public boolean closed;\n   public boolean opened;\n\n   public Chest(int xpos, int ypos, int numContents, ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; idList, boolean opened, boolean closed)\n   {\n     this.closed = true;\n     this.opened = false;\n   }\n\n }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>How I fixed it<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Chest chest = new Chest(0,0,0, new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;(),false,false);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Thank you micha!<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 22871918,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "arraylist"
        ],
        "score": 0,
        "accepted_answer_id": 22871952,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 217,
        "last_edit_date": 1396641477
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/SwKRE.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 1129042,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1115554,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1115554/micha",
                "reputation": 49842,
                "display_name": "micha",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1396641447,
            "creation_date": 1396641447,
            "body": "<p>You can do this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Chest chest = new Chest(0, 0, 0, new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;(), false, false);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>If you want to to add values to the list you can use <code>Arrays.asList()<\/code> as a shortcut:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;Integer&gt; list = Arrays.asList(1,2,3);\nChest chest = new Chest(0, 0, 0, list, false, false);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 22871952,
            "question_id": 22871918
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/ww6TF.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2095246,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1864167,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1864167/jeroen-vannevel",
                "reputation": 44565,
                "display_name": "Jeroen Vannevel",
                "accept_rate": 90
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1396641448,
            "creation_date": 1396641448,
            "body": "<p>A simple way:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>chest = new Chest(0,0,0, Arrays.asList(5, 6, 7),false,false);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This will cause a problem with <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; idList<\/code> in your constructor though. You should <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2697783/what-does-program-to-interfaces-not-implementations-mean\">probably change<\/a> that to <code>List&lt;Integer&gt; idList<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>If not, you can use <\/p>\n\n<p><code>new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(Arrays.asList(5, 6, 7))<\/code> as my original answer showed.<\/p>\n\n<p>See: <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Arrays.html#asList%28T...%29\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>Arrays.asList(T... a)<\/code><\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 22871953,
            "question_id": 22871918,
            "last_edit_date": 1495540195
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/142c3537ba70a0cadb1b241f9eb69540?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 64432,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 190201,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/190201/ataylor",
                "reputation": 66369,
                "display_name": "ataylor",
                "accept_rate": 83
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1396641508,
            "creation_date": 1396641508,
            "body": "<p>You can initialize it with:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>new Chest(0, 0, 0, Arrays.asList(0), false, false)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Note that the return type is <code>List&lt;Integer&gt;<\/code> rather than <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;<\/code>, which is probably what you want anyway.  There's probably no need to specify which specific implementation of the interface <code>List<\/code> to use in the class declaration.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you want to initialize it to an empty list, you can use:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>new Chest(0, 0, 0, Collections.emptyList(), false, false)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Note in both cases, you get an immutable list.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 22871974,
            "question_id": 22871918
        }
    ],
